<!-- ========== BPC-157 ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>BPC-157: The Gut Repair Specialist</h2>

<div class="cd cb">
  <div class="tg">Compound Profile</div>
  <h3>Body Protection Compound-157</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Sequence:</strong> 15-amino acid peptide derived from human gastric juice &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Primary Actions:</strong> Tissue regeneration, angiogenesis, anti-inflammatory &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Routes:</strong> Oral (preferred for gut), subcutaneous injection &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Research Status:</strong> Extensive animal data, limited human trials &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>FDA Status:</strong> Not approved; research compound</p>
</div>

<p><a href="/articles/bpc-157-complete-guide">BPC-157</a> is arguably the most studied peptide for gastrointestinal healing. It's derived from a protein found naturally in human stomach acid, which gives it a unique advantage: it survives the harsh digestive environment and acts directly on intestinal tissue (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10432032/">Sikiric et al., 1999</a>).</p>

<p>Its mechanism centers on strengthening tight junctions between intestinal epithelial cells. These junctions act as gatekeepers, controlling what passes from the gut lumen into the bloodstream. When they weaken, partially digested food particles, bacteria, and toxins leak through, triggering systemic inflammation.</p>

<h3>How BPC-157 Heals the Gut</h3>

<p>BPC-157 works through multiple overlapping pathways that collectively accelerate mucosal repair. It increases vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) and fibroblast growth factor (FGF), which drive the formation of new blood vessels in damaged tissue (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29898106/">Seiwerth et al., 2018</a>).</p>

<p>This angiogenic effect is critical. Damaged gut tissue is often poorly supplied with blood, which starves healing cells of the oxygen and nutrients they need. By restoring blood flow to injured areas, BPC-157 creates the conditions for repair to occur naturally.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Research Finding</div>
  <p>In animal models of induced colitis, BPC-157 normalized gut function within days. It reduced ulcer size, accelerated fistula healing, and decreased inflammatory markers at the injury site (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10432032/">Sikiric et al., 1999</a>).</p>
</div>

<p>BPC-157 also modulates the nitric oxide (NO) system, which plays a central role in gut motility and blood vessel regulation. This helps normalize bowel movement patterns in both constipation-dominant and diarrhea-dominant conditions.</p>

<h3>BPC-157 Dosing for Gut Issues</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Dose Range</th><th>Frequency</th><th>Duration</th><th>Best For</th></tr></thead>
