  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Sequence:</strong> 37-amino acid peptide &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Type:</strong> The only human cathelicidin antimicrobial peptide &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Primary Actions:</strong> Antimicrobial, immunomodulatory, barrier reinforcement &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Routes:</strong> Oral, subcutaneous &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Key Application:</strong> SIBO, infection-related gut issues</p>
</div>

<p><a href="/articles/ll-37-antimicrobial-peptide-guide">LL-37</a> is unique among gut-healing peptides because it serves a dual role. It directly kills harmful bacteria, viruses, and fungi while simultaneously regulating immune function. Your body produces LL-37 naturally as a first-line defense, but levels are often depleted in people with chronic gut conditions (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32316534/">Gombart, 2020</a>).</p>

<p>This peptide is especially valuable for Small Intestinal Bacterial Overgrowth (SIBO). Unlike broad-spectrum antibiotics that wipe out everything, LL-37 selectively targets pathogenic organisms while preserving the beneficial microbiota your gut needs to function properly.</p>

<h3>LL-37's Dual-Action Protection</h3>

<p>LL-37 destroys pathogens by disrupting their cell membranes, a mechanism that bacteria struggle to develop resistance against. It's effective against gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, enveloped viruses, and certain fungi (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32316534/">Gombart, 2020</a>).</p>

<p>On the immune side, LL-37 modulates both innate and adaptive immunity. It enhances the activity of macrophages and neutrophils (your body's pathogen-clearing cells) while preventing excessive inflammation that damages healthy tissue.</p>

<div class="d-a">
  <div class="s">Important Note</div>
  <p>Some users experience temporary Herxheimer-like reactions (fatigue, mild digestive upset) when starting LL-37, as pathogen die-off releases endotoxins. Start at lower doses and increase gradually. These symptoms typically resolve within 3&ndash;5 days.</p>
</div>

<h3>LL-37 Dosing Protocols</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Protocol</th><th>Dose</th><th>Timing</th><th>Duration</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>SIBO / bacterial overgrowth</strong></td><td>200&ndash;500 mcg</td><td>Once daily, empty stomach</td><td>4&ndash;8 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>General gut defense</strong></td><td>100&ndash;200 mcg</td><td>Once daily</td><td>2&ndash;4 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Post-antibiotic recovery</strong></td><td>100&ndash;300 mcg</td><td>Twice daily</td><td>2&ndash;6 weeks</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Start at 100 mcg daily and titrate upward over 5&ndash;7 days. Combining LL-37 with a quality probiotic supports microbial rebalancing during treatment.</p>

<!-- ========== COMPARISON TABLE ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Comparing the Three Gut Peptides</h2>

<p>Each of these peptides targets a different aspect of gut dysfunction. Understanding their strengths and limitations helps you determine which one (or which combination) fits your situation best.</p>

<table class="tbl">
